<content type="str">Our country has a new president, duly elected legally by the voters of this nation. We, as citizens, need to stand by him and give him our allegiance and honor. This is America and this is the way things are done here. 
 
The citizens have spoken and those who wanted someone else must accept the fact that there is one winner and one loser in any election. 
 
Some recent events have shamed our country and caused other nations to lose confidence in our way of government. No one group of persons is better or worse than any other group and the color of one’s skin or being male or female doesn’t give any group the right to think they are better than anyone else or to try to destroy our country. True Americans stand together, united, even if they wish another candidate had won. Riots never did any good to anyone and only show the ignorance of those destroying what does not belong to them. 
 
Let’s hope and pray that we, as a nation, can get past this disobedience and become what we used to be, the example of being a noble nation. 
 
As a citizen of the United States, this is what I believe. Laws have been made to help citizens live together in peaceful communities. I may not agree with all of them, but I will do my best to obey them. That is the duty of every citizen. 
 
There are only ten basic laws that govern all mankind. These fundamental laws are the basis on which the laws of our country are based. Many thousands of patriots have given their lives to protect and keep America. It is the duty of every one of us to help keep her free. As a citizen, I pledge to honor and obey the laws of this country, honor our flag, support our leaders, and to support those who risk their lives to preserve our freedom. I am proud to be an American citizen. 
 
It is important for the youth of our country to know the history of our country and the history of their ancestors. There has been a push to record the stories of fathers and grandfathers who were in World War II. 
 
Time is of an essence since that generation is thinning rapidly. It is traumatic for those who have faced the horrors of war to talk about it, and only decades after their experiences have many of them told their stories. It has been helpful for those in later years to record what they have experienced and it is what young folks today need to know about those who protect all of us. 
 
The ancestors of all of us (except the Native Americans) came from somewhere else, and many of those came to this country because of war. The stories of how they became citizens and learned the language and culture of their new country are important for each family. The traditions they brought with them is part of our culture now. 
 
I met many folks in Europe when I lived there that told me what they, as children, went through during the war in their country. You do not want your children to have to face some of the horrors that they faced. I remember how scared I, as a child was, during World War II, and there was no fighting here in this country. We cannot let our county become so weak that anyone thinks they can “take us on” and create war on our shores. 
 
We need to let our young family members learn what their ancestors had to endure to become citizens in a strange land so that they can prevent harm on our shores as they become the governing age. Educate them in the traditions of your family. Leave them with journals of your life and the recipes of their grandmothers. Teach them the morays of family life so that they will have a contented and happy life. There is so much hate and violence in our world today that we have to show them that there is a better way to live. We need to show, by example, that no one should tolerate lawlessness and violence, or the loss of our freedom and our country. They need to learn to be Americans, as there is so much against our way of life at the present time, and much of it is internal. 
 
The recipes today are for comfort foods. We all need them, especially, when we feel depressed and worry about our country. Pray for our president. And, add to your prayer list all those who protect us, those who need a “helping hand.” 
 
May God Bless you and God Bless America. 
 
